  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap5.pdf_4_33",
    "text": "We use similar language to that on page 210, with appropriate modifications:",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.11654135670298316,
      0.7863372090746333,
      0.7255638963045357,
      0.8023313491546766
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_chap5.pdf_4",
    "order": 36
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap5.pdf_4_34",
    "text": "The SLR(1) parsing algorithm. Let s be the current state whose number is at the top of the parsing stack. Then actions are defined as follows:",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.11466164731454456,
      0.8211805559716008,
      0.8327067403255666,
      0.8546626980743935
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_chap5.pdf_4",
    "order": 37
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap5.pdf_4_35",
    "text": "(1) If state s contains any item of the form A → a. X B, where X is a terminal, and X is the next token in the input string, then the action is to remove the current input token and push onto the stack the number of the state containing the item A → aX. B.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.11466165461903152,
      0.8561046515642801,
      0.8815789420651954,
      0.9099702378528107
    ],
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_chap5.pdf_4",
    "order": 38
  }
]